The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

NATION BRIEFS

 Hyderabad, Aug. 5: The Andhra Pradesh government may derecognise private schools that pressurise students with crude methods of punishment to boost results. 

 State school education minister D. Raja Narasimha made the announcement following complaints that some schools were coercing students from as early as Class VI to prepare for competitive exams like the IIT entrance. 

 New Delhi (PTI): The Maharashtra government has given a clean chit to an orphanage in Pune against which Denmark had made allegations of irregularities in adoptions, leading that country to suspend adoption from India. A probe has found that the allegations were ill-founded.

 Thiruvananthapuram (PTI): A zoo has been closed and 19 wild boars culled after foot-and-mouth disease resurfaced. The authorities are finding it difficult to contain the virus as it is carried by wind. The disease has claimed 25 animals including black bucks and nilgai since an outbreak in June. 

 New Delhi (PTI): Traffic policemen in plainclothes will travel on Blueline buses to keep a close watch on drivers. The move comes after a series of accidents involving the buses, which prompted the government to pull them off the roads.

 Chennai (PTI): Over 330 live Star tortoises being smuggled into Malaysia have been seized from a passenger at the airport. He said the bag was handed to him inside the airport by one Shahjahan and he agreed to carry it for Rs 2,000. 

 New Delhi (PTI): A 22-year-old engineer allegedly committed suicide by hanging himself in his house in Greater Kailash. Priyank Pathak, the son of a brigadier, was unemployed for some time, police said.




